	* Prayer Meeting


------------------------
	*Expenses App* (probably not suitable as a Web App?)
------------------------
The Expenses app (to be developed) must allow the following workflow:
1) Claimant fill in an online form to submit claim. Form includes ability to upload multiple forms of evidence (ie invoice/bill) paperwork
2) Upon submission, the Treasury dept receives an email confirming a new claim has been submitted. The relevant authorisors also receive an email advising that new claims need authorisation. A PDF of the claim should be attached.
3) Authorisors (there can be multiple, this is defined by which department the claim is logged under and can also be determined by the value of the claim) can click a link in the email to "login" and Authorise or Decline a claim. This triggers an action to the Treasury to advise of an update, and to the claimant
4A) If Authorised, the Treasury responses by clicking a link in their notification email to log and complete reimbursement, where they can also enter one (or more) internal reference numbers for the reimbursed payment. A PDF of the claim and progress up to this point should be saved, ut not emailed
4B) If not authorised, no further action is required, but the record remains for audit purposes. Claimant and Authorisers should however be emailed to confirming the Declined authorisation, with a PDF of the claim form with a "NOT APPROVED" Diagonal watermark overlayed attached to the email and saved for record purposes on the server.
5) Once Reimbursement has been issued, the both the authoriser and the claimant receive confirmation that payment has been initiated, and the claim has been closed. This confirmation email should have a PDF of the claim updated status of the claim form attached, including "COMPLETE" overlayed as a diagnoal watermark. The email should lso allow the claimant to raise a follow-up query (after 7 working days) if payment has not yet been received.
Local and MS365/Google Workspace connected functionality should apply not just to the Portal subdomain but to the entire domain name.
			

------------------------
*Use of Database*
------------------------
All records must be logged in the backend database

------------------------
	*Activity Logging/Audit Trail*
------------------------
All activity also logged in an ActivityLog (tblActivityLog) in the backend database, including:
* Action taken,
* User account who performed the action
* date/time action was performed
* Was action successful or errored
* IP Address from which action was initiated (both IPv4 & IPv6). Take into account use of proxies and services similar to CloudFlare, and try to log the users action IP not CloudFlare/proxy IP
* Browser/client useragent where action was initiated
* Original requested URL
* Original Request Header
tblActivityLog is nOT just for logging errors, but ALL activity. Given some apps will handle financial or other confidential info, data integrity, data quality and data auditing is crucial - hence the need for tblActivity. Details of errors should be logged in tblErrors
Logging all Activity in the ActivityLog would assist with troubleshooting, and allow for developers/Admins/Global Admins to identify and fix issues, or simply use as an audit trail if any malicious activity is suspected.



------------------------
	*Log All Errors/Warning/Notificaions*
------------------------
All Errors/Warnings/Notifications from PHP or any other service/library/tool used should be looked to a tblErrors table. Like tblActivityLog, the following data points must be logged
* Error Platform (the Platform/tool Libary where the error occured: ie PHP, MySQL, dompdf, MS365, Google Workspace, Paypal, faceID, Javascript etc)
* Error Severity (such as, but not limited to: Notification, Warning, Error, Fatal etc)
* Platform Specific Error Code
* Platform returned error description
* Platform returned error detail
* Timestamp of error 
* User account who performed the action
* IP Address from which action was initiated (both IPv4 & IPv6). Take into account use of proxies and services similar to CloudFlare, and try to log the users action IP not CloudFlare/proxy IP
* Browser/client useragent where action was initiated
* Original requested URL
* Original Request Header
* Whether or not error has been reviewed/resolved (for tracking fixes etc - will be managed via a Error Log UI available to Global Admins within the Portal)

------------------------
	*Sending E-mails*
------------------------
Emails should be sent with Microsoft Graph via a Microsoft 365 account using a shared mailbox (with appropriate permissions), not standard PHP Send especially as we want to ensure all mail is appropriately secure via DKIM, DMARC and other requirements

------------------------
	*Security & User Authentication*
------------------------
 * User authentication is key! CSRF, sessions, cookies and other security methods should be used throughout to ensure only the appropriate people can do certain tasks.
 * User logins should primarily be (Especially for authorisors, admins, Root/Global Admins and Finance/Treasury team) via Microsoft 365 user account, where username, full name, email address and avatar are collected.
	* This should then also create a "local" account (linked to the MS365 account) for future/backup use.
	* Claimants can login using either local or MS365 account, though its important to note that NOT all claimants will have a valid MS365 account.
 * Support for Google accounts should also be prepared for, though this may only be implemented later, as we do not have a Google Workspace account/tenant yet.
 * It should be possible to link a LOCAL ACCOUNT, MS365 & Google Workspace account together to allow (eventual) login with either and still use the system as the same single user.
	* We may also integrate login via other third-party platform accounts in future
		* Meta (Facebook, Instagra, Threads, WhatsApp)
		* Apple Account
		* Google Account
		* WordPress
		* Microsoft Account (personal)
		* LastPass
	  in all cases they should be linked to a local account, and if one does not already exist, one should be created (and again, for key roles, linked to a valid/appropriate MS365).
	* Local User Accounts (when not using third-party services for login) should also support the following technologies on supported devices/platforms
		* Windows Hello
		* Fingerprint (Touch ID)
		* Facial Recognition (Face ID) login should also be supported on all supported devices.



------------------------
	*Web Page Design*
------------------------
* Web pages should be fully responsive, and accommodate all screen sizes & orientations
* Should also be compliant with all current standards
* Should take accessibilty into WCAG compliant to support users with impairements, including a toggle for colour blind users and screenreader support.
* Fully HTML5 compliant and use the latest and greatest HTML5 features, whilst also "gracefully" falling back for browsers that do not support them.
* Styling of the UI should use modern CSS including CSS 3+ and can make use of modern/advanced switches and even animations.
* Pages should indicate to the user that they're logged in, by showing something in the top-right corner (as is commonly the norm in the industry).
  This should display
	* User avatar (in this priority order: MS365/Google Workspace etc > Locally stored profile picture from tblUSers in database > Gravatar > default/placeholder avatar)
	* Name of user
	* A means to change user profile settings (possible via drop-down menu when clicking on Name and Avatar)
* ALL config (with the exception of database connection credentials) should be stored in the Backend MySQL Database (tblSettings table).
* Some settings, like MS365/Google Workspace etc credentials should also be able to be stored in a private location on the server as a fallback.
* It should also be possible for new settings to be added at any time by a Global Admin using the Web UI, and minimised requirement to have to manually update PHP Code too much to take these new settings to account.
* Values for settings marked as 'isSensitive' (as well as fields storing ANY user passwords) should be appropriately cryptographically encrypted/hashed to current industry standards, also using a salt for increased security, to ensure these are safe/secure - but also allow them to be internally decrypted for use as/when required.
* Whilst PHP will be used, the end user should not see this even in places like webpage/form/processor URLs. Not only is this unprofessional but it could also be a security risk as it exposes to potential attackers that PHP is used. Therefore all URLs should be visible as /something/somepage. This can perhaps be achieved by either a router (managed/tored in SQL database), or by simply ensuring the content is in a a location like /something/somepage/index.php (as in the case of the above example)
* Appropriate user-facing error handling should also be implemented, as well as backend error handling for server-side PHP scripts and log these into the Activity Log for later development and fixing by the development and Global Admin teams.
* Form fields (for ALL apps) should
	* Have dynamic field validation wherever possible
	* Use datepickers to ensure consistent format for entered dates.
	* Use ReCaptcha or CloudFlare Turnstile, provided the relevant API Keys are provided (preferred backend database, but fallback in auth.php). If no API Keys provided dont use these technologies for form submission.

It would also be useful, and user-friendly to have the ability to design the PDF files produced by the system using wither a blocks-based WYSIWYG editor (where various 'sections' are represented by blocks than can be added/moved/resized into place) or the ability to upload the template as an HTML file. In both cases (WYSIWYG and html upload), their should be the ability to use 'placeholder text markers' that will be replaced by the relevant data (text or images) when the PDF is created/

development versions for each app will be placed in public_html_dev folders (as opposed to public_html for "fully released versions"

Can we also consider implementing access control for alpha and beta versions of app to limit who's can access.

For further flexibility, some future apps may only be accessible via a payment (one-off or subscription). support for this also needs to be built, with payment accepted via PayPal (also via Apple Pay or Google Pay on supported platforms/devices), and payment records, status and access availability needs to also all be stored in the backend database

A Portal "home page" should be created in public_html/ with a list of the various "app" users can browse to.

Additional "Dashboards" should also be created as required.

All code (including SQL) should be fully/completely commented/annotated in detail, to assist with understanding of code and functionality, make code readable and also assist with future learning and debugging. Code should also be properly indented for improved human readability. Happy to use emojis in comments to help "call-out" sections of comments. 

We would also like to use AJAX where possible to dynamically load/change content to avoid entire page refreshes. However use of AJAX should not be a blocker if a browser doesnt support/have javascript/AJAX enabled. it should still be possible to use everything in the portal/sub-apps without AJAX
Please use Bootstrap, and other technologies/libraries (FontAwesome etc) to achieve the required functionality, but please note the project will be hosted on Dreamhost Shared Hosting, so any libraries will need to be manually downloaded and uploaded as Compile and similar functionality is not available. Happy to use libraries from CDNs as a priority, but would be good to have a fallback to selfhosted should CDNs be down.

Any graphics/icons should be in SVG (Vector) to improve scalability and should offer a Base64 encoded fallback for browsers/clients that do not support SVG. (SVG support should be detected dynamically wherever possible). Animated SVG (vector) are also acceptible for icons

We're trying to achieve wide compatibility and a user friendly feel, especially some users may not be computer savvy.

For users, each should be able the assigned to multiple Departments (abbrev Depts), and multiple Groups, where there is no necessary correlation/link between Dept and Groups. (think of Groups as Committees/working groups). Each Dept can have a Lead and some assistants/team members). In some cases a (such as the case for the Expenses app) Dept Lead must be the one of the authorised for expenses within that department. Some Departments may even require multiple two or more authorisations from within the department (with also the ability to make the lead a mandatory authorisor of these), this should also be definable and stored in the database as appropriate. In other cases, the Dept Lead AND Treeasury may need to authorise an expense claim (such as if claim value is above a threshold, also configurable held within the Settings)
All of this should be stored in the structured backend database (an example of database structure SQL below)
Database table named should have "tbl" prefix, followed by the Name of the App (eg Expenses) if that table is only used for that specific App. portal/side-wide tables (Users etc) do not need an 'App' prefix (again, see example db structure)


You will note the existing MySQL Database's tblSettings table (which is used to store settings for the Portal as a whole as well as individual 'apps', uses a notation of '.' delimited hierarchy for the settings "keys". When retrieving all settings, plus can these be converted into a PHP multidimentional array $Settings[], split on the '.' delimiter.


There should also be various types of users including:
* User (default)
* Claimant - same permissions as User type
* Editor - for future use
* Moderator - for future use
* Admin - ability to edit some settings in the front end UI. Must use MS365/Google Workspace login, or a local account with 2FA and PassKey and an associated/already linked MS365/Google Workspace login.
* Global Admin - (ie security and developers only) ability to edit all settings in the front end UI, including those settings labelled as 'isSenstive'. Also has the ability to add new settings via the front end UI.  Must use MS365/Google Workspace login, or a local account with 2FA/PassKey and an associated MS365/Google Workspace login

There are likely to be additional apps launched in future, so please bear that in mind when building structure (directory, code, database and sql). We want to share/use the same content as much as possible and not have too much code/resource duplication.

With this in mind, we're looking for a modular design/development structure with a focus on functionality, security, data integrity as well as flexibility/scalability

Primary development environment will be on Mac OS (Windows occassionally) with Visual Studio Code as our IDE where we also intend to use the ftp-sync extension. Wee would like to have a GitHub repo to manage the development and staging of the project. please also suggest the best way to setup and manage this project within a GitHub repo (use of GitHub Secrets, GitHub Project, GitHub Issues, GitHub Actions, GitHub Agents, GitHub Wikis, GitHub Sponsorships, GitHub Discussions. Propose/Configure these as it would work best for a project like this.

The Existing GitHub Repo/IDE evironment may already have files in them from a previous iteration. please feel free to make any changes necessary for this brief. Any files/folders no longer needed should be deleted.


Please include intended file path in the "header comments" of this and every file going forward, alongside Copyright info, which should start in 2025 and end in the current year (that is dynamic and managed in the Repo). Copyright Organisation is "MWBM Partners Ltd (t/a MWservices)"

Whilst this is mainly a web-portal platform, please also manage version numbering and keep references to this in file headers also.


Before we start, can you summarise the current platform and a summary/build plan ahead of starting dev.

I'd like to keep a track of build progress at each stage, and log these in Project_Status.md

Please also produce a suitable README.md and and CHANGELOG.md and keep it up to date with every change/as we progress. 

Please also store any Claude memory, or prompt history in .claude/ to help us as we progress.

this is a somewhat complex, multi-"module" project for a organisation "Intranet poral" for volunteers, staff and leaders.

We want this to be well developed and organised. As such, please ensure the following Standing Instructions and tasks are actioned:

* For each new action (which will either be to implement a fix, enhance functionality or brand new functionality) please ensure a GitHub Issue/task is created to help track all the tasks and keep our progress going. Give a thorough description within each GitHub Issue, along the lines of "Whats the problem, whaat are we adding/creating", including Proposed Scope checks, and Acceptance Criteria checks.
* Once the work is completed, update the GitHub Issue/Task in question with the status and close if the task is fully complete. Also link/include the COMMIT number(s) that dealt with the issue/task in question
* Run ALL code through thorough Syntax, Lint and similar checks, fixing ALL issues regardless of age (new or pre-exissting) or severity (fix warnings, issues, bugs, fatal errors, discrepancy warnings, recommendations etc). Security checks should be included, checking for all security "holes", including all user inputs are sanatised to prevent injections. Repeat until ZERO issues are found. We wnat CLEAN code, as this minimises further issues down the line.
* Update GitHub Wiki, GitHub Project, GitHub Milestones alongside GitHub Issues.
* Update local documents including CHANGELOG.md, DEV_NOTES.md, README.md
* Update .claude/ memory, context and prompts
* COMMIT Changes (DO NOT PUSH, we'll PUSH mannually)

ALSO, ALWAYS ensure all code is well commented/annotated including inline comments as well as comment blocks. This will help with further development, maintenance, code learning and understanding.
Ensure all PHP code blocks are written in there full annotation with suitable indentation,no shortened versions. This makes code more human readable. If we want to keep code to a minimum or somewhat obfuscated, we can always minify it as part of the code upload process via GitHub Actions